{"slideshow_credits": null, "snippet": "To the founders, separation from Britain was about racial fear and exclusion as much as it was about inalienable rights....", "abstract": "Op-Ed article by author and assistant Prof Robert G Parkinson asserts Declaration of Independence is as much about racial fear and exclusion as it is about freedom and inalienable rights; holds country's founders raised opposition to British by linking them with threat posed by Native Americans or rebellious slaves; contends idea that some people belong as proper Americans while others do not has long marked our history.", "section_name": "Opinion", "print_page": "21", "document_type": "article", "byline": {"person": [{"lastname": "PARKINSON", "rank": 1, "firstname": "Robert", "role": "reported", "organization": "", "middlename": "G."}], "original": "By ROBERT G. PARKINSON", "contributor": ""}, "web_url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/04/opinion/did-a-fear-of-slave-revolts-drive-american-independence.html", "lead_paragraph": "To the founders, separation from Britain was about racial fear and exclusion as much as it was about inalienable rights.", "headline": {"print_headline": "A Declaration of Fear", "main": "Did a Fear of Slave Revolts Drive American Independence?", "content_kicker": "Op-Ed Contributor", "kicker": "Op-Ed Contributor"}, "_id": "577a0e7738f0d837d446502c", "word_count": "942", "multimedia": [{"height": 126, "url": "images/2016/07/04/opinion/04parkinson/04parkinson-thumbWide.jpg", "legacy": {"wideheight": "126", "wide": "images/2016/07/04/opinion/04parkinson/04parkinson-thumbWide.jpg", "widewidth": "190"}, "subtype": "wide", "width": 190, "type": "image"}, {"height": 385, "url": "images/2016/07/04/opinion/04parkinson/04parkinson-articleLarge.jpg", "legacy": {"xlarge": "images/2016/07/04/opinion/04parkinson/04parkinson-articleLarge.jpg", "xlargewidth": "600", "xlargeheight": "385"}, "subtype": "xlarge", "width": 600, "type": "image"}, {"height": 75, "url": "images/2016/07/04